2. Backing bean: add dedicated methods

Do not reuse the full edit method.

```java
public class SponsorApplicationAdminBean {

    private Application selectedApplication;
    private Long selectedCustomerCategoryId;
    private List<SelectItem> customerCategoryOptions;

    public void prepareCustomerCategoryUpdate(Long applicationId) {
        selectedApplication = sponsorApplicationService.getApplicationById(applicationId);

        if (selectedApplication != null) {
            selectedCustomerCategoryId = selectedApplication.getCustomerCategoryId();
        }
    }

    public void updateCustomerCategoryOnly() {
        if (selectedApplication == null || selectedApplication.getApplicationId() == null) {
            addErrorMessage("No application selected.");
            return;
        }

        if (selectedCustomerCategoryId == null) {
            addErrorMessage("Customer Category is required.");
            return;
        }

        sponsorApplicationService.updateCustomerCategoryOnly(
                selectedApplication.getApplicationId(),
                selectedCustomerCategoryId,
                getLoggedInUser()
        );

        refreshApplicationList();
        addInfoMessage("Customer Category updated successfully.");
    }

    private void refreshApplicationList() {
        applicationList = sponsorApplicationService.getApplications(searchCriteria);
    }

    private void addInfoMessage(String message) {
        FacesContext.getCurrentInstance().addMessage(null,
                new FacesMessage(FacesMessage.SEVERITY_INFO, message, null));
    }

    private void addErrorMessage(String message) {
        FacesContext.getCurrentInstance().addMessage(null,
                new FacesMessage(FacesMessage.SEVERITY_ERROR, message, null));
    }

    // getters/setters
}
```

3. Service layer: separate business method

This is the important part.

Your existing `edit/update application` path probably contains reference validation like:

```java
if (isReferencedInSponsorApplicationMap(applicationId)) {
    throw new BusinessException("Application record cannot be edited...");
}
```

Do not remove that.

Instead, add a new service method that updates category only and intentionally does not call that validation.

```java
public void updateCustomerCategoryOnly(Long applicationId, Long customerCategoryId, String updatedBy) {
    Application application = sponsorApplicationDao.findById(applicationId);

    if (application == null) {
        throw new BusinessException("Application not found.");
    }

    application.setCustomerCategoryId(customerCategoryId);
    application.setUpdatedBy(updatedBy);
    application.setUpdatedDate(new Date());

    sponsorApplicationDao.updateCustomerCategoryOnly(application);
}
```

4. DAO layer: update only one column

This should be a narrow update, not a full entity merge if you want maximum safety.

JPA version:

```java
@Transactional
public int updateCustomerCategoryOnly(Long applicationId, Long customerCategoryId, String updatedBy) {
    String jpql =
            "update Application a " +
            "set a.customerCategoryId = :customerCategoryId, " +
            "    a.updatedBy = :updatedBy, " +
            "    a.updatedDate = :updatedDate " +
            "where a.applicationId = :applicationId";

    return entityManager.createQuery(jpql)
            .setParameter("customerCategoryId", customerCategoryId)
            .setParameter("updatedBy", updatedBy)
            .setParameter("updatedDate", new Date())
            .setParameter("applicationId", applicationId)
            .executeUpdate();
}
```

JDBC version:

```java
public int updateCustomerCategoryOnly(Long applicationId, Long customerCategoryId, String updatedBy) {
    String sql =
            "UPDATE APPLICATION " +
            "SET CUSTOMER_CATEGORY_ID = ?, UPDATED_BY = ?, UPDATED_DT = SYSDATE " +
            "WHERE APPLICATION_ID = ?";

    return jdbcTemplate.update(sql, customerCategoryId, updatedBy, applicationId);
}
```

Replace `APPLICATION` with your actual table/entity name.

5. Keep the existing validation exactly where it belongs

Current full edit flow should remain:

* blocked if referenced in `SPONSOR_APPLICATION_MAP`

New category-only flow should be:

* not blocked by `SPONSOR_APPLICATION_MAP`
* only updates `CUSTOMER_CATEGORY_ID`

That cleanly satisfies both business rules.

What not to do

Do not do this:

* remove the existing reference validation from the normal edit flow
* reuse the full edit screen and disable fields conditionally
* call a generic `saveApplication()` method that updates all fields
* let the popup bind directly to the full application object and then `merge()` everything blindly

That would make the story risky and can accidentally change other fields.

Safer naming

Use explicit method names so future developers do not misuse them:

* `prepareCustomerCategoryUpdate(...)`
* `updateCustomerCategoryOnly(...)`

Avoid generic names like:

* `editApplicationSpecial`
* `saveApplicationLite`

Recommended icon/button label

If icons are image-based like your current screen, use one of these:

* tooltip: `Update Customer Category`
* alt text: `Category`
* optional visible label if needed: `Cat`

If your team prefers text buttons, use:

* `Update Category`

My recommendation:
icon + tooltip, because your current grid already uses compact row actions.

